{{about|the Central African language}}
'''Ibinda''' (also ''Kibinda'', ''Chibinda'', ''Tchibinda'') is ostensibly a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]] or a dialect group spoken in the [[Angola]]n [[Provinces of Angola|province]] and [[exclave]] of [[Cabinda Province|Cabinda]].
[[File:LanguageMap-Kikongo-Kituba.png|thumb|Dialect map of Kongo and [[Kituba]].]] Ibinda is [[Western Kongo]] ([[Malcolm Guthrie|Guthrie]]: H16d) as it is spoken in Cabinda.<ref>The dialect "of the region around the Kongo rapids is called Ki-kongo, or Mfiote." From "The Province of Angola." Report by Commercial Agent Chatelaine, of [[Luanda|Loanda]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=3f4oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA572#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''The Miscellaneous Documents of the House of Representatives for the Second Session of the Fifty-Second Congress 1892-'93''.] p.572.</ref> It is a combination of several dialects of the [[Kongo language]] (Kikongo) spoken by small ethnic groups in Cabinda. Among the principal ones are Iwóyo, Ikuákongo (Kakongo), Ikóchi, Ilínji (Ilinge), Kiyómbe (Quiombe), Kisúndi and Ivili<ref name="Língua Nacional"/> although some are sometimes considered separate from Ibinda.<ref>Elizera Teixeira João and Vitália Rodrigues. [http://www.teiaportuguesa.com/cabinda/cabinda.htm Excursão Virtual a Cabinda.] Retrieved 15 January 2010. {{pt icon}}</ref><ref>Jouni Filip Maho. [http://goto.glocalnet.net/mahopapers/nuglonline.pdf "NUGL Online: The online version of the New Updated Guthrie List, a referential classification of the Bantu languages."] Version of 4 June 2009. p. 52. Retrieved 15 January 2010.</ref> Ibinda is a project of [[Front for the Liberation of the Enclave of Cabinda|Cabindan separatists or nationalists]] who advocate the formation of a [[Republic of Cabinda]] and is the "[[national language]]" of the proposed state.<ref>[http://www.cabinda.net/start.htm Republic of Cabinda: People] at the Republic of Cabinda website. Retrieved 15 January 2010.</ref>
Historically, vernacular speech in Cabinda has also been called '''Fiote''', from ''m'fiôte'', a word meaning "black" or "colored person."<ref name="Spotlight">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-adv/specialsales/spotlight/angola/article14.html "Cabinda: Society – Language Matters."] in ''International Spotlight: Angola'', A special advertising site produced by [[washingtonpost.com]]. Retrieved 15 January 2010.</ref> Fiote referred to all local languages of Cabinda "because they were the languages spoken by black people." The term was also used to describe the inhabitants themselves and as an adjective meaning native or indigenous ("everything that was not of European origin was labeled 'fiote' – fiote papaya, mango fiote, potato fiote, etc.<ref name="Língua Nacional">[http://www.cabinda.net/ibinda.html "Cabindês, Fiote ou Ibinda: Língua Nacional de Cabinda."] Retrieved 15 January 2010. {{pt icon}}</ref>). However, this term is considered derogatory and is eschewed by Cabindans. "Cabindans do not like being called Fiote...[because] the word was used by the Portuguese to describe everything that was inferior – a bad road would be called a fiote road and bad food would be called fiote food."<ref name="Spotlight"/> Some argue that the language should be called '''Cabinda'''.<ref name="Língua Nacional"/>
