{{about|an Indo-Aryan language of central India|the language isolate also known as Nahali|Nihali language}} {{Infobox language |name=Kalto |nativename=Nahali |region=[[Nandurbar district|Nandurbar]] and [[Jalgaon District]]s, on the border of [[Maharashtra]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] |speakers=15,000 |date=2003 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] |fam4=[[Western Indo-Aryan languages|Western Indo-Aryan]] |fam5=[[Bhil languages|Bhil]] |iso3=nlx |glotto=naha1261 |glottorefname=Nahali }}
'''Kalto''', or '''Nahali''', is an [[Indo-Aryan language]] of [[languages of India|India]]. Kalto is the [[endonym]]; the exonym "Nahal" or "Nihal" is disparaging. Because of the name "Nahali", the language has often been confused with [[Nihali language|Nihali]], an apparent [[language isolate]] spoken by a neighbouring people with a similar lifestyle.
