{{Infobox language |name = Noni |region =[[Cameroon]] |speakers ={{sigfig|53,200|1}} |date=2005–2008 |ref=e18 |familycolor =Niger-Congo |fam2 =[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3 =[[Benue–Congo]] |fam4 =[[Southern Bantoid]] |fam5 =[[Eastern Beboid languages|Eastern Beboid]] |fam6 =Noni |dia2 =Ncane |dia3 =Mungong |dia1 =Noone |lc2 = ncr |ld2 = Ncane |lc1 = nhu |ld1 = Noone |script = [[Latin script|Latin]] |glotto=noon1243 |glottoname=Noone |glotto2=ncan1245 |glottoname2=Ncane }}
The '''Noni language''', also called '''Noone''', is an [[Eastern Beboid language]] of the [[Niger–Congo]] family in [[Cameroon]]. The Noone, Ncane, and Mungong varieties are sometimes considered three distinct Noni languages. ''Ethnologue'' reports that Ncare is 88% lexically similar with Noone, and 84% with [[Saari language|Saari]] (Nsari).
Noni is the [[native language]] to 40,000 people in the country, particularly in the [[North-West Province, Cameroon|North West Province]], the Bui Division and the northwest [[Kumbo]] Subdivision. Noone proper was used as the secret language in Indiana Jones.
==References== {{reflist}} *[[Larry Hyman|Hyman, Larry M.]] 1980. Noni (Misaje group). L’expansion bantou. Paris: SELAF (no. special 9), 259–274. *Hyman, Larry M. 1981. Noni grammatical structure, with special reference to verb morphology. Southern California: Occasional Papers in Linguistics 9. Los Angeles: University of Southern California. *Lux, David 2003. Noni provisional lexicon. ms. Yaoundé: SIL *Richards, Russell M. 1991. Phonologie de trois langues beboides du Cameroun: Noone, Ncanti et Sari. Thèse pour le doctorat (Arrête du 23 Novembre 1988), Livres I. et II. Université de la Sorbonne Nouvelle Paris III.
